<br>
  I wonder how much you know about the Magician class when you rattle off and inform me that because I'm not anywhere near the 'end game' (what is that, anyways, killing Kerafyrm?), that what I have to say is total nonsense, that it's obviously flawed, and totally off base.<br>
<br>
  While I have yet to actually go into duel mode with the various pets and see whether or not a wizard/necro can nuke them with the elements they're supposed to be immune against, what I have seen is encouraging to the fact of their relative immunity.<br>
<br>
--Fire pets (as mentioned) are the sole meleers against Lord Rak'ashiir (or whatever his name is) in the City of Mist. If you aren't aware, Lord Rak has a fire based, high damage (around 2k points per hit), lure style (as I understand it, I thought it was just regular resists) AoE. If you're caught in it, you're dead, unless you're kept alive by healers constantly. Something not many tanks involve themselves in. I watched Lord Rak start chewing through a raid one day because we had just 2 fire pets on it, and we were fighting in the back hallway. Well, I watched people get owned as Rak was kicked by the pets back towards the group. The pets.. beyond taking melee damage (ie: only one who had rak's attention) ever took damage, the other fire pets figured it tickled, I guess.<br>
<br>
--Earth pets in Fungus Grove. Checking the Spdat.eff file using the eqcaster program, I come across the Shrieker's Curse, Shrieker calm, and Shrieker slow spells, all disease based. Now, I've fought in Fungus for a while, off and on. During my time fighting there, never ONCE has my earth pet ever been slowed by the mushrooms. You can tell, because, being a duration based spell, you will see a 'such and such has worn off' message, and never once have I seen that. Considering the level difference, and that those shrooms DO turn and slow anyone nearby, and that my pet has tanked some before, that seems to indicate to me that they're highly (if not more) resistant to these disease based spells.<br>
<br>
--Water pets, a long time ago I was taught and learned to use my low level water pets against poisonous snakes. The water pets never ever seemed to get poisoned, so this worked out for the best, right? Well, as I understand it, it extends to more than just snakes, as you yourself mention, as others have told me.<br>
<br>
--Air pets. Sadly, I have not had much of a chance to try this for myself, to have any solid first-hand evidence to present to anyone, but what I have heard is that others have used this pet on cold based AoE mobs and found it acceptably resistant.<br>
<br>
NOTE: Dragons are NOT on the same style resistances as normal creatures. No matter how resistant you are, occasionally, you WILL take damage from a dragon's AoE. This .. 'immunity vulnerability', if you want to call it that, extends to even the pets, so their supposed 'immunity' only applies as 'high resistance' against dragons.<br>
<br>
Now, of course, take anything I say with a grain of salt, though depending on what you call 'end game' stuff, I might have done <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I get more experience as I raid more (yay guild!), but things like pets having immunities, oddly enough, IS NOT INFO THAT IS AQUIRED ONLY DURING END GAME ENCOUNTERS <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
P.S. I never once said that everything was all 'hunky dory' with the Magician class. I said things aren't as bad as they're made out to be, and that these niggling pieces of information such as pet immunities are things that aren't readily apparent, and could cost magicians pain in the long run by not knowing it.<br>
<br>
Ie: Had I known that the air pet was immune to cold and not the water pet, when I went up against Terror in the Plane of Fear, I could've offered more damage output against it. I could've helped take that monster down a bit faster. As it was, the raid we were on BARELY managed to kill that particular Demi, with like 4-5 people remaining alive, not enough to deal with the demi's guards. Against creatures that do not fear (though dispell), your pet is free damage, a possible (for me at level 55) 56x4 + bash/kick a round. If I can tailor my assault so that my pet lives long enough to do suitable damage, how is this bad? Besides, if it dispells Burnout, reapply. Have see invis memmed and a few levi rings. As effects fade through dispelling, reapply ad nausium to protect the haste buff. If it's that big a mob, you just might do better damage with a pet in melee rather than nuking.<br>
<br>
I don't question that we have issues (ie: larger pet-caused aggro radius, horrific pathing, amungst other issues). Perhaps pets could a little bit of a boost in power. I tend to think that might be fixed through rare drop foci items (ones that can actually be achieved instead of the foci that are so rare or so screwed up in design as to be unworthy to get). Perhaps a chain quest foci item might help too (rare drops to add into the Foci to improve it's power). That just wasn't the point of my argument <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Rhasin Firestorm<BR>
